        id: 'environment-drift',
        title: 'Environment drift and refresh risk',
        objective: 'Detect and control environment drift across configuration, dependencies, schema, data, and deployment history.',
        instruction: [
          'Environment drift occurs when environments differ in ways that were not intended or understood. Drift may involve code version, configuration, infrastructure, dependency version, database schema, reference data, feature flags, permissions, or test fixtures. Some differences are necessary, but undocumented differences weaken test evidence.',
          'A refresh can reduce drift by copying schema or approved data patterns, but it can also erase active test records, import sensitive data, reset flags, or break integrations. Refreshes therefore need scope, backup, communication, validation, and recovery.',
          'Implementation leaders use environment comparison rather than assumptions. Compare artifact version, migration version, dependency endpoints, configuration keys, role access, flag state, and representative business controls before a high-risk test or release.',
        ],
        standard: 'Maintain automated or reviewable environment comparison for release-critical configuration and schema, and govern refreshes as changes with impact and validation.',
        controls: ['Define allowed and disallowed differences.', 'Compare versions and configuration before UAT.', 'Protect active test evidence during refresh.', 'Validate data masking and access after refresh.'],
        failures: ['Staging lacks the latest database migration.', 'A refresh restores an obsolete feature-flag state.', 'Production-only permissions are not represented in UAT.', 'Test evidence disappears because refresh timing was not coordinated.'],
        scenarioTitle: 'A staging pass cannot be reproduced',
        scenarioContext: 'The same test fails after a weekend refresh, and no one knows which schema or configuration changed.',
        decision: 'What should the team compare and preserve?',
        recommendation: 'Compare deployment and migration versions, configuration inventory, dependency endpoints, flags, access roles, refresh logs, and test-data identifiers. Restore only through the approved baseline and document the drift cause before rerunning acceptance.',
        labTitle: 'Create an environment drift checklist',
        labBrief: 'Define expected similarities and permitted differences for the capstone environments.',
        labSteps: ['List code, schema, configuration, dependency, flag, and access comparisons.', 'Mark intentional differences.', 'Define refresh prechecks and backups.', 'Create post-refresh validation evidence.'],
        evidence: ['Drift checklist', 'Allowed-difference register', 'Refresh validation plan'],
        answerGuide: ['The checklist extends beyond code version.', 'Intentional differences have rationale and owner.', 'Refresh protects active evidence and sensitive data.', 'Post-refresh validation confirms schema, access, and integration health.'],
        takeaways: ['Drift is dangerous when differences are invisible, not merely when they exist.', 'Refreshes are changes and can create new risk.', 'Environment comparison strengthens the meaning of test evidence.'],
        sourceIds: ['twelve-factor-config', 'nist-ssdf-1-1'],
        visualTitle: 'Environment drift control loop',
