        title: 'Backward-compatible APIs and expand-and-contract database changes',
        objective: 'Sequence API and database changes so old and new application versions can coexist safely during rollout.',
        instruction: [
          'Backward-compatible API changes add behavior without breaking existing consumers. Database expand-and-contract first adds compatible structures, then migrates and verifies use, and only later removes old structures. This supports mixed versions during rolling or canary deployment.',
          'A safe sequence might add a nullable column, deploy code that writes both old and new representations, backfill and reconcile data, shift readers, monitor, then remove the old column in a later release. The exact sequence depends on engine, volume, constraints, and application behavior.',
          'Backfill is a production data operation with performance, restart, duplicate, and reconciliation concerns. Rollback may require keeping both structures until the observation period ends. Contract removal should follow consumer evidence and deprecation communication.',
        ],
        standard: 'Use backward-compatible intermediate states for mixed-version releases, separate destructive contraction from initial deployment, and reconcile every backfill before removing old behavior.',
